            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is negative gearing?</h2>
              <p>
                In Australia, <strong>negative gearing</strong> happens when the
                costs of holding an investment (usually a rental property) are
                higher than the income it produces. The investment runs at a
                loss before tax, but that loss can generally be offset against
                your other income (such as salary), reducing your overall tax
                bill.
              </p>
              <p>
                Many investors accept a small cash loss each year in the hope
                that <strong>capital growth</strong>
                on the property will more than compensate over time. The tax
                deduction from negative gearing reduces the size of the loss,
                but it does not turn a poor investment into a good one.
              </p>

              <h2>How this negative gearing calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                The calculator models a single year of rental income and
                expenses for a residential investment property. It separates:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cash flow</strong> – money actually paid in or out
                  (rent, interest, bills, repairs).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Non‑cash deductions</strong> – mainly depreciation and
                  capital works.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Taxable income or loss</strong> – what the ATO taxes
                  you on after deductions.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Loan amount and interest</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Loan amount</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Loan} = \text{Purchase price} \times (1 -
                  \text{Deposit \%}/100)\)
                </p>
                <p><strong>Interest (interest‑only)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Interest} = \text{Loan} \times \text{Interest rate
                  \%}/100\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you choose <strong>principal &amp; interest</strong>, the
                calculator assumes a 30‑year term and uses the standard
                amortisation formula to estimate the annual repayment. It then
                splits that into:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Interest</strong> – tax‑deductible.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Principal</strong> – not tax‑deductible, but it
                  reduces your loan balance.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Rental income</h3>
              <p>Annual rent is calculated as:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>\(\text{Annual rent} = \text{Weekly rent} \times 52\)</p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If you want to allow for vacancy (e.g. 2 weeks empty per year),
                reduce the weekly rent or multiply by fewer weeks (e.g. 50
                instead of 52).
              </p>

              <h3>3. Cash expenses</h3>
              <p>
                Cash expenses include interest plus all the running costs you
                enter:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Council and water rates</li>
                <li>Insurance</li>
                <li>Repairs and maintenance</li>
                <li>Strata / body corporate fees</li>
                <li>Property management fees</li>
                <li>
                  Other deductible expenses (e.g. advertising, travel where
                  allowed)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Total cash expenses</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Cash expenses} = \text{Interest} + \text{Other cash
                  costs}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Pre‑tax cash flow</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Pre‑tax cash flow</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Pre‑tax cash flow} = \text{Annual rent} - \text{Cash
                  expenses}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If this number is negative, your property is
                <strong>cash flow negative</strong> before tax.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Taxable income or loss</h3>
              <p>
                For tax purposes, you can usually deduct both cash expenses and
                eligible non‑cash deductions such as depreciation and capital
                works.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Taxable income</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Taxable income} = \text{Annual rent} - (\text{Cash
                  expenses} + \text{Depreciation})\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                If taxable income is negative, you have a
                <strong>tax loss</strong> that can generally be offset against
                your other assessable income in that year (subject to ATO
                rules).
              </p>

              <h3>6. Tax impact and after‑tax cash flow</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Tax impact</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If taxable income &lt; 0 (loss):<br />
                  \(\text{Tax saving} = |\text{Taxable income}| \times \text{Tax
                  rate}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  If taxable income &gt; 0 (profit):<br />
                  \(\text{Extra tax} = \text{Taxable income} \times \text{Tax
                  rate}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>After‑tax cash flow</strong></p>
                <p>
                  If loss:<br />
                  \(\text{After‑tax cash flow} = \text{Pre‑tax cash flow} +
                  \text{Tax saving}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  If profit:<br />
                  \(\text{After‑tax cash flow} = \text{Pre‑tax cash flow} -
                  \text{Extra tax}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>7. Effective yields</h3>
              <p>
                To give you a quick sense of scale, the calculator also shows
                the pre‑tax and after‑tax yields relative to the purchase price:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \(\text{Pre‑tax yield} = \dfrac{\text{Pre‑tax cash
                  flow}}{\text{Purchase price}}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{After‑tax yield} = \dfrac{\text{After‑tax cash
                  flow}}{\text{Purchase price}}\)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Interpreting your results</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Negative pre‑tax cash flow</strong> means you are
                  tipping in money each year to hold the property.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tax saving</strong> reduces that loss but does not
                  make the investment profitable on its own.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>After‑tax cash flow</strong> shows the real impact on
                  your pocket each year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You should also consider
                  <strong
                    >capital growth, interest rate risk, vacancy risk and
                    buffers</strong
                  >.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes you are an Australian resident individual for tax
                  purposes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Uses a single marginal tax rate including Medicare levy, not
                  the full ATO tax scale.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Ignores land tax, CGT, offset accounts, redraw, and complex
                  structures (trusts, companies).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Models one year only; it does not project multiple years or
                  changing interest rates.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For personalised advice, speak with a licensed financial adviser
                or registered tax agent.
              </p>

              <h2 id="faq">Negative gearing FAQ</h2>

              <h3>Is negative gearing legal in Australia?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. Under current Australian tax law, rental property losses
                can generally be offset against other income, subject to ATO
                rules. Policy settings can change over time, so always check the
                latest guidance.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I always aim for negative gearing?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Many investors now prefer
                <strong>neutral or positive cash flow</strong> properties,
                especially in a higher interest rate environment. Negative
                gearing can magnify gains in a rising market but also magnifies
                losses if prices fall or rents drop.
              </p>

              <h3>What expenses are usually deductible?</h3>
              <p>
                Common deductible expenses include interest on the investment
                loan, council and water rates, insurance, property management
                fees, repairs and maintenance, strata fees, and eligible
                depreciation and capital works. Some items have specific rules,
                so check the ATO website or ask your tax adviser.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator replace tax advice?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This tool is for
                <strong>education and planning only</strong>. It simplifies the
                Australian tax system and cannot account for every personal
                circumstance. Always confirm important decisions with a
                qualified professional.
              </p>
